Email Extractor
README & Code Documentation
Purpose
The Email Extractor is a Go programme that scans a block of text and pulls out every valid email address it finds, ignoring surrounding punctuation, sentences, and unrelated words. It is built entirely with Gos standard strings package — no regular expressions are used.

Where It Can Be Used
• Contact form scrapers — pull emails out of pasted text or documents
• Data cleaning pipelines — extract emails from messy datasets or logs
• Email marketing tools — gather addresses from customer feedback or support tickets
• Spam/security filters — identify and flag email addresses in raw text
• Educational projects — demonstrate string parsing and validation in Go

Programming Language
Language: Go (Golang)
• Version: Go 1.18+
• Packages used: fmt, strings
• No external dependencies and no regexp required
 Extraction Rules
Condition
Result
Word contains no @ symbol
Skipped
Word has more than one @ symbol
Skipped (invalid)
Nothing before the @ symbol
Skipped (invalid)
No dot in the domain part after @
Skipped (invalid)
Exactly one @, valid local part, dot in domain
Extracted as email


Full Code
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "strings"
)

func extractEmails(text string) []string {
    var emails []string
    words := strings.Fields(text)

    for _, word := range words {
        word = strings.Trim(word, ".,!?;:<>\"'()")

        if strings.Contains(word, "@") {
            parts := strings.Split(word, "@")

            if len(parts) == 2 && parts[0] != "" && strings.Contains(parts[1], ".") {
                emails = append(emails, word)
            }
        }
    }
    return emails
}

func main() {
    text := "Contact us at admin@test.com or support@gmail.com."
    emails := extractEmails(text)
    for _, e := range emails {
        fmt.Println(e)
    }
}

Line-by-Line Explanation

Package & Imports
package main
Declares this file as the entry point of the Go program. Every executable Go program must have package main.

import ( "fmt"  "strings" )
Imports two standard library packages:
• fmt — used to print output to the terminal
• strings — provides functions for splitting, trimming, and searching text

Function: extractEmails
func extractEmails(text string) []string {
Defines a function named extractEmails that takes the full block of text as input and returns a slice of strings — the list of extracted emails.

var emails []string
Creates an empty slice to collect every valid email address found in the text.

words := strings.Fields(text)
Splits the text into individual words wherever whitespace occurs. For example, the sentence becomes a slice like ["Contact", "us", "at", "admin@test.com", "or", "support@gmail.com."].

for _, word := range words {
Loops through every word in the slice, one at a time. The underscore discards the index since only the word itself is needed.

word = strings.Trim(word, ".,!?;:<>\"'()")
Removes any of the listed punctuation characters, but only from the start and end of the word — never the middle. This strips a trailing period off something like support@gmail.com. so it becomes support@gmail.com.

if strings.Contains(word, "@") {
Checks if the current word contains an @ symbol at all. This is a fast first filter — ordinary words like 'Contact' or 'us' are skipped immediately since they have no @.

parts := strings.Split(word, "@")
Splits the word wherever an @ appears. For 'admin@test.com' this produces ["admin", "test.com"] — the local part and the domain part separated.

if len(parts) == 2 && parts[0] != "" && strings.Contains(parts[1], ".") {
Three conditions must all be true for the word to count as a valid email:
• len(parts) == 2 — there is exactly one @ symbol, not zero and not more than one
• parts[0] != "" — something exists before the @ (the local part is not empty)
• strings.Contains(parts[1], ".") — the domain part after @ contains a dot, like .com or .org

emails = append(emails, word)
Only runs if all three validation conditions passed. Adds the cleaned word to the emails slice as a confirmed valid email address.

return emails
After the loop finishes checking every word, the function returns the completed slice of extracted emails.

main() Function
text := "Contact us at admin@test.com or support@gmail.com."
emails := extractEmails(text)
for _, e := range emails { fmt.Println(e) }
The main() function is the entry point of the program. It defines a sample text, calls extractEmails on it, and prints each extracted email on its own line.

Sample Output
Input Text
Extracted Emails
Contact us at admin@test.com or support@gmail.com.
admin@test.com


support@gmail.com


How to Run
• Save the code in a file called main.go
• Open your terminal in the same folder
go run main.go
The extracted email addresses will print to your terminal, one per line.

